ImageDescription{<5}WaiIntro
11	The traditional greeting
12	known as the wai ,
13	where you press your hands together
14	as is in prayer
15	and bow slightly ,
HowToWai{>6}WaiOriginAndProminence
16	is derived from the Hindu cultural influence from India ,
17	and still widely practised .
IntroTheWai{>4}WaiInstructions
18	Among Thais , there are strict rules of hierarchy
19	that dictate how and when the wai should be given .
20	In brief , inferiors salute superiors first .
21	You should not wai service people or street vendors .
WhenToDoWai{>6}MoreDescription
22	The higher your hands go ,
23	the more respectful you are .
24	You will also often see
25	Thais doing a wai
26	as they walk past temples and spirit houses .
HowThaiPeoplePracticeWai{=5}ExpectationsForForeigners
27	As a foreign visitor , you are not expected to know how to wai ,
28	nor to reciprocate
29	when wai'd to ;
NotExpectedToWai{>7}Hypothetical
30	while you 're unlikely to cause offense
31	if you do ,
32	you may well look slightly strange .
ExpectationsForForeigners{=6}AcknowledgeWai
33	If somebody makes a wai to you ,
34	a slight bow alone is more than sufficient for ordinary occasions ,
35	and for business , most Thais will shake hands with foreigners instead of waiing anyway .
